A Machine Learning Approach to Cation Identification for Solubility Optimization Of Redox Active Material for Non-aqueous Redox Flow Batteries

Motivation

As renewable energy sources like wind and solar gain traction, efficient energy storage becomes crucial for grid stability. Redox flow batteries (RFBs) offer promising solutions, with non-aqueous RFBs (NRFBs) showing distinct advantages like wider temperature range and higher energy density.3 The solubility of active materials is a critical factor in determining the energy density of NRFBs. However, synthetically exploring a large parameter space to identify soluble species is an inefficient approach. To expedite NRFB material discovery and optimization, this work explores the transformative role of computation and machine learning.

Methods Overview

Model system used in this study is alkylammonium vanadium bis-hydroxyiminodiacetate as shown below (V+4: [cation]2[VBH]; V+5: [cation][VBH]). Where there exist a wide variety of possible cation molecules Solvent: Acetonitrile

- The surrogate model designed in this study was trained and tested using a dataset of 119 molecules for both [VBH]2- and [VBH]1- (total of 238 molecules), containing features related to molecular geometry

- The solubility of 150 quaternary ammonium cations were predicted using the trained model

Dependencies

The following dependencies were used for this study:

Scikit-learn : A free software machine learning library for the Python programming language.(see :https://scikit-learn.org/stable/)

RDKit : An open-source toolkit for cheminformatics (see: https://www.rdkit.org/)

Matplotlib : a plotting library for the Python programming language and its numerical mathematics extension NumPy (see:https://matplotlib.org/)

Pandas : a software library written for the Python programming language for data manipulation and analysis (see:https://pandas.pydata.org/)

Feature selection

Correlation Analysis

Correlation analysis was used to select features to use for this study. Features with above a specified certain correlation coefficient with eachother (correlation threshold) were removed from the data. Finding a suitable correlation threshold was an iterative process which was dependent on model performance

def evaluate_correlation(dataset):
    plt.figure(figsize = (24, 16))
    corr = dataset.corr()
    with sns.plotting_context(context ="poster",font_scale=0.9):
        heatmap = sns.heatmap(corr,annot=True,cmap="GnBu",vmax=1,vmin=-1)
    plt.show()

# adjust dataset
def adjust_data(dataset):
    ''' filters out features with correlation coefficient >= 0.95 with each other'''

    # filter features with high correlation with each other
    upper_tri = dataset.corr().abs().where(np.triu (np.ones (dataset.corr().abs().shape), k=1).astype (bool))
    to_drop = [column for column in upper_tri.columns if any(upper_tri[column] >= 0.97)]
    dataset= dataset.drop (dataset [to_drop], axis=1)
    #test
    return dataset
    

adjusted_data1 = adjust_data(df1)
evaluate_correlation (adjusted_data1)

Evaluate model

The function below was uesd to evaluate the different regression models. The evaluation metrics used for this study were R-2 and RMSE metrics.. Cross plots were also created for each model. Cross plots, also known as scatter plots, are essential tools in machine learning for visually examining the relationship between two variables. They help identify correlations, patterns, and outliers, enabling data scientists to explore data, select relevant features, and interpret model predictions. By plotting one variable on the x-axis and another on the y-axis, cross plots provide valuable insights into data distribution and class separability in classification tasks. These simple yet powerful visualizations aid in understanding the data's characteristics, guiding feature selection, and facilitating informed decision-making throughout the machine learning process.

In [ ]:
#score models

def score_model(model,x_train,x_test,y_train,y_test,show= False):
    '''
    Returns R-2 and RMSE values on test and train set for input model as a list. This function outputs a crossplot if show parameter is set to True
    '''
    # predict data 
    pred_test = model.predict(x_test)
    pred_train = model.predict(x_train)

    
    #score predictions with r2 and rmse
    score_list = []
    train_r2 = r2_score(y_train, pred_train)    
    test_r2 = r2_score(y_test, pred_test)    
    train_rmse = mean_squared_error(y_train, pred_train, squared = False)    
    test_rmse = mean_squared_error(y_test, pred_test, squared = False)

    score_list.extend((train_r2, test_r2, train_rmse, test_rmse))

    # visualize metrics
    if(show):
        # print scores
        print("Trian set R-sqaure  : ", r2_score(y_train, pred_train))        
        print("Test set R-square : ", r2_score(y_test, pred_test))        
        print("RMSE on training set : ", np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_train, pred_train)))        
        print("RMSE on test set : ", np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, pred_test)))

        # visualize prediciton
        plt.figure()
        plt.scatter(y_train, pred_train,color="blue", alpha=0.8, label="train")
        plt.scatter(y_test, pred_test, color="red", alpha=0.8, label="test")
        p1 = max(max(pred_train), max(y_train))
        p2 = min(min(pred_train), min(y_train))
        plt.plot([p1, p2], [p1, p2], 'k-')
        plt.xlabel("actual Log(So)")
        plt.ylabel("predicted Log(So)")
        plt.legend(loc = 'best')
        plt.show

    else :
        return score_list

Ranking features by importance

The function below was used to create a plot of the different features ranked by thier feature importancee for tree-based models

In [ ]:
def plot_feature_importance(model):
    #Create arrays from feature importance and feature names
    feature_importance = np.array(model.feature_importances_,)
    feature_names = np.array(x_train1.columns)

    #Create a DataFrame using a Dictionary
    data={'feature_names':feature_names,'feature_importance':feature_importance}
    fi_df = pd.DataFrame(data)
    my_range=range(1,len(fi_df.index)+1)

    #Sort the DataFrame in order decreasing feature importance
    fi_df.sort_values(by=['feature_importance'], ascending=True,inplace=True)
    
    # The horizontal plot is made using the hline function
    plt.hlines(y=my_range, xmin=0, xmax=fi_df['feature_importance'], color='skyblue')
    plt.plot(fi_df['feature_importance'], my_range, "o")
    
    # Add titles and axis names
    plt.yticks(my_range, fi_df['feature_names'])
    plt.xlabel('Feature Importance')
    plt.ylabel('Features')

    # Show the plot
    plt.show()

Boosting Algorithms

Boosting is a popular ensemble learning technique in machine learning that sequentially builds multiple weak learners to create a strong learner. Each weak learner focuses on correcting the errors made by its predecessors, effectively improving the overall model's performance. The most common boosting algorithms include AdaBoost, Gradient Boosting, and XGBoost, each with its variations and strengths. Boosting iteratively gives higher weights to misclassified data points, allowing subsequent weak learners to focus on these challenging cases. As a result, the ensemble becomes more robust and accurate, even with complex datasets and noisy features. Boosting has become a widely used approach due to its ability to handle various types of data and provide highly accurate predictions. However, it can be sensitive to outliers and might require careful tuning to avoid overfitting. In summary, boosting is a powerful ensemble technique that iteratively improves the model's accuracy by combining multiple weak learners. It has proven to be effective in a wide range of machine learning tasks, making it a popular choice for predictive modeling.

Adaptive Boost

AdaBoost is an ensemble learning algorithm that combines weak learners to improve accuracy. It assigns higher weights to misclassified data and iteratively updates them, leading to a more accurate model. Effective in binary classification tasks, AdaBoost is widely used in face detection, object recognition, and bioinformatics. Its ability to leverage weak learners effectively makes it a valuable tool in machine learning.

Redisual Comparison for Different Models

Residual distribution plots are graphical representations of the differences between actual and predicted values in regression models. They help evaluate the model's performance and assumptions by examining patterns in the residuals' distribution. A well-behaved residual plot shows a mean close to zero, consistent spread of residuals across predictions (homoscedasticity), and independence of residuals. Deviations from these patterns can indicate issues like bias, non-linearity, or outliers, prompting data scientists to improve the model iteratively. In summary, residual distribution plots offer valuable insights into model accuracy and guide refinements for better predictive performance in machine learning tasks.

In [ ]:
def resplot(models,label,x_test,y_test):
    model_names = ["AdaBoost","RandomForest","XGBoost","CatBoost","DecisionTree","LinearRegression","ExtraTrees"]
    residuals = []
    mods=[]

    for model in models:
        res = y_test - model.predict(x_test)

        for i in res:
            residuals.append(i)
            mods.append(model_names[models.index(model)])

    d = pd.DataFrame(data={'models': mods, 'residuals': residuals})


    displot = sns.displot(data=d, x="residuals", hue="models", kind="kde",height=5, aspect=1).fig.suptitle(label,fontsize=14)
    plt.show()

def pred_LogSo(model,data):
    ''' returns dataframe and solubility predictions
    '''
    smiles = [smi for smi in data["Cat_SMILES"]]
    LogSo = [LogSo for LogSo in model.predict(new_data.drop("Cat_SMILES",axis =1))]

    d = {'Cat_SMILES': smiles, 'Log(So)': LogSo}
    return pd.DataFrame(data=d)

# use RDKIt to draw grid on molecules and solubility for top 15 molecules
def show_best(data):

    best_mol = data.sort_values(by=['Log(So)'],ascending= False).head(15).reset_index(drop = True)
    
    mols  = [Chem.MolFromSmiles(smi) for smi in best_mol["Cat_SMILES"] ]
   
    
    return rdkit.Chem.Draw.MolsToGridImage([m for m in mols if m is not None], molsPerRow=5, subImgSize=(300, 200),legends=[str(round(x, 4)) for x in best_mol["Log(So)"]])
